printf can print out a number of data types to console. To do this, placeholders, delimited using %, are put in the format string
of the function call, and then in a separate field of the function call the variable that corresponds to that data type is specified.

==Common Data Types==
%c  - Character
%d  - Integer
%s  - C-String
%f  - Float
%lf - Long Float (aka Double)
%u  - Unsigned Integer

==Uncommon Data Types==
%o  - Octal
%p  - Pointer
%x  - Hexadecimal

Usage:
...

    int myInt = 15;
    char myString [] = {'B', 'O', 'B'};
    
    printf("Name: %s Age: %d", myString, myInt);    // Output: Name: BOB Age: 15
    printf("Integer Casted as Hex: %x", myInt);     // Output: Integer Casted as Hex: f
    
...
